\section{Questions to be handed in for project 2: Functions in Julia}\newline
Read about this \href{http://mth229.github.io/functions.html}{here}.\newline
For the impatient, it is easy with \texttt{Julia} to create basic mathematical functions, as the notation is identical:\begin{verbatim}
f(x) = x^2 - 2
f(2)
\end{verbatim}
\begin{verbatim}
2\end{verbatim}
\newline
As with typical mathematical notation, the function is "called" by passing a value to it with parentheses.\newline
That covers most of the uses within this project.\rule{\textwidth}{1pt}
\newline
But there is more to functions...\subsubsection{Julia functions can have more than one variable}\begin{verbatim}
rectarea(b, h) = b * h		# area of rectangle
\end{verbatim}
\begin{verbatim}
rectarea (generic function with 1 method)\end{verbatim}
\newline
The \texttt{log} function is an example, where \texttt{log(b,x)} will find the log base $b$ of $x$.\subsubsection{Julia functions with different signatures, can have the same name!}\begin{verbatim}
rectarea(b) = rectarea(b,b)	# area of square using area of rectangle
\end{verbatim}
\begin{verbatim}
rectarea (generic function with 2 methods)\end{verbatim}
\newline
Which function is used depends on the arguments that are passed when calling the function. Hence, \texttt{log(x)} will find log base $e$ of $x$ whereas \texttt{log(10,x)} can be used to find log base 10.\subsubsection{Multiline functions are defined with the function keyword}\begin{verbatim}
function multiline_function(x)
	 top = x^2 - 2x
	 bottom = x^4 - 4x
	 top/bottom		# last line is return value
end				# don't forget the end
\end{verbatim}
\begin{verbatim}
multiline_function (generic function with 1 method)\end{verbatim}
\subsubsection{Functions can have keyword arguments (like parameters). These have default values:}\begin{verbatim}
mxplusb(x; m=0, b=1) = m*x + b
mxplusb(10, m=3, b=4)		# arguments are named
\end{verbatim}
\begin{verbatim}
34\end{verbatim}
\newline
The semicolon separates the two types of arugments.\subsubsection{Functions can be used as arguments to other functions:}\begin{verbatim}
using Plots	    		# for plotting
gadfly()
plot(sin, 0, 2pi)		# pass function for first argument plot(f,a,b)
\end{verbatim}
\begin{html}

\end{html}
\newline
Using functions this way will form a \textit{very} common pattern.\subsubsection{Functions can be anonymous.}\newline
These are defined via the pattern: "\texttt{args -> body}". Look for the arrow \texttt{->}:\begin{verbatim}
plot(x -> sin(x)*cos(2x), 0, 2pi)
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Cases}\newline
Some functions are defined in terms of cases. For example, a cell phone plan might depend on the data used through:\begin{quotation}\newline
The amount is 40 dollars for the first 1 Gb  of data, and 10 dollars more for each \textit{additional} Gb of data.\end{quotation}\newline
This function has two cases to consider: one if the data is less than 1 Gb and the other when it is more.\newline
How to write this in \texttt{julia}?\newline
The ternary operator \texttt{predicate ? expression1 : expression2} has three pieces: a predicate question, such as \texttt{x < 10} and two expressions, the first is evaluated if the predicate is \texttt{true} and the second if the predicate is \texttt{false}. They are useful to write functions that are defined by cases. (They are a light-weight form of the traditional \texttt{if-then-else} construct.)\newline
The example above, could then be done with:\begin{verbatim}
f(d) = d <= 1.0 ? 40.00 : 40.00 + 10.00 * (d - 1.0)
\end{verbatim}
\begin{verbatim}
f (generic function with 1 method)\end{verbatim}
\begin{itemize}\item Write a function to express the following: If a person buys up to   100 units the cost per unit is 5 dollars, for every additional unit   beyond 100 the cost is 4 dollars. The function should return the   total cost to buy $x$ units. (Use the ternary operator with \texttt{x <=   100} as the condition.\end{itemize}
\\begin{answer}
type: longtext
reminder: Total cost for x units
answer_text: \verb#f(x) = x <= 100 ? 5.0 * x : (5.0*100) + 4*(x-100) # 
rows: 3
cols: 60
\\end{answer}
\begin{itemize}\item Use the ternary operator to write a function $f(x)$ which takes a   value of $x$ when $x$ is less than 10 and is otherwise a constant   value of 10.\end{itemize}
\\begin{answer}
type: shorttext
reminder: Function which is x for x < 10 and 10 otherwise
answer: f(x) = x < 10 ? x : 10

\\end{answer}
\begin{itemize}\item Define a function $Sin(x) = \sin(x)$ if $-\pi/2 < x < \pi/2$ and   \texttt{NaN} otherwise.\end{itemize}
\\begin{answer}
type: shorttext
reminder: restrict sin(x) to -pi/2 to pi/2
answer: Sin(x) = -pi/2 < x < pi/2 ? sin(x) : NaN

\\end{answer}
\begin{itemize}\item Define a function \texttt{signal(x)} where when $x \leq 0$ the function is $0$, when $x > 1$ the function is $1$, and otherwise is $\sin(\pi/2 \cdot x)^2$.\end{itemize}\newline

You can used two ternary operations, or the easier to read \texttt{if-elseif-end} pattern which looks something like:\begin{verbatim}

  ...

  ...

  ...
end
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Composition}\newline
Composition of functions is a useful means to break complicated problems into easier to solve ones. The math notation is typically $f(g(x))$ and in \texttt{julia} this is no different. When thinking about the operation of composition, the notation $f \circ g$ is used. For that, there isn't any built-in \texttt{julia} notation.\begin{itemize}\item For the function $h(x) = ((x+1)/(x-1))^{2/3}$ write this as the   composition of two functions $f(x)$ and $g(x)$. Use these to evaluate   $h(3)$. Show your work and the answer.\end{itemize}

\subsection{Returning a function}\newline
Familiar mathematical functions take a real number and return a real number. However, the concept of a function is more general. With \texttt{julia} it is useful to write functions that take functions as arguments, and return a derived function as an output. For the return value an \textit{anonymous function} is typically used. These are specified as \texttt{arg -> rule}, where the arg is a variable, like \texttt{x}, and the rule can depend on the value of \texttt{x}.\begin{itemize}\item Describe what the following function does to the argument $f$, when   $f$ is a function. (There isn't anything to do but recognize that   \texttt{n} takes a function as input and returns a function as output, this   question is how is \texttt{n(f)} related to \texttt{f}.)\end{itemize}\begin{verbatim}
n(f::Function) = x -> -f(x)
\end{verbatim}
\begin{verbatim}
n (generic function with 1 method)\end{verbatim}

\\begin{answer}
type: longtext
reminder: Describe \verb+n(f::Function) = x -> -f(x)+
answer_text: The defines g(x) = -f(x) 
rows: 3
cols: 60
\\end{answer}
\begin{itemize}\item This function takes a function and two points and returns a new function that evaluates the secant line:\end{itemize}\begin{verbatim}
function secant(f, a, b)
  m = (f(b) - f(a)) / (b - a)
  x -> f(a) + m * (x - a)
end
\end{verbatim}
\begin{verbatim}
secant (generic function with 1 method)\end{verbatim}
